'''Hysteroid dysphoria''' is a name given to repeated episodes of depressed mood in response to feeling rejected.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=1480561 |year=1992 |last1=Møller |first1=SE |title=Serotonin, carbohydrates, and atypical depression |volume=71 Suppl 1 |pages=61–71 |journal=Pharmacology & toxicology |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0773.1992.tb01630.x}}</ref>

Hysteroid dysphoria has been described in outpatient populations and is thought to be a subtype of [[atypical depression]] involving [[rejection sensitivity]] and therapeutic response to [[MAOI|monoamine oxidase inhibitor]]s.<ref>http://www.psycom.net/hysteroid.html {{cite journal |year=1984 |last1=Beeber |first1=AR |last2=Kline |first2=MD |last3=Pies |first3=RW |last4=Manring |first4=JM Jr |title=Hysteroid dysphoria in depressed inpatients |volume=Apr;45(4) |pages=164–6 |journal=Journal of Clinical Psychiatry}}</ref>{{Psych-stub}}

