'''Pelvic massage''' is a gynecological treatment first recorded as being used by doctors in the 19th century. An early practitioner was [[Thure Brandt]], whose method was described in the ''[[New York Medical Journal (1865)|New York Medical Journal]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/opinion/comment/victorian-doctors-were-not-using-vibrators-on-female-patients-it-was-even-stranger-than-that/|title=Victorian doctors were not using vibrators on female patients – it was even stranger than that|date=2018-11-12|work=inews.co.uk|access-date=2018-11-13|language=en-GB}}</ref> and the [[Journal of the American Medical Association|''Journal of the American Medical Association'']].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=NORDHOFF|first=SOFIE A.|date=1895-03-16|title=KINETIC THERAPEUTICS IN GYNECOLOGY OR THURE BRANDT'S SYSTEM.|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/452037|journal=Journal of the American Medical Association|language=en|volume=XXIV|issue=11|pages=389|doi=10.1001/jama.1895.02430110007001a|issn=0002-9955}}</ref>
